SIMPLE: exaltation
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Exaltation
<hw>Ex`al*ta"tion</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>exaltatio</ets>: cf. F.<ets>exaltation</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>The act of exalting or raising high; also, the state of being
exalted; elevation.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Wondering at my flight, and change⟦br⟧
To this high <qex>exaltation</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Alchem.)</fld> <def>The refinement or subtilization
of a body, or the increasing of its virtue or principal
property.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Astrol.)</fld> <def>That place of a planet in the
zodiac in which it was supposed to exert its strongest
influence.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <fld>(Med.)</fld> <def>An abnormal sense of personal
well-being, power, or importance, -- a symptom observed in various forms
of insanity.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Exalted</ent>⟦br⟧
